<subSubSection lastPageId="81" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="81" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
Prostrate perennial herb, densely tomentose on all vegetative parts, often brownish when dry. Leaves petiolate, 1.2-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-2.5 cm, variable in shape, ovate, lanceolate-deltoid or, most commonly oblong, margin undulate to crenate, base hastate to sagittate; petioles 3-6 (-20) mm. Flowers solitary, axillary, pedunculate; peduncles solitary or, occasionally, paired, 1.5-4 cm, often arching; bracteoles 5-7 
<pageBreakToken pageId="81" pageNumber="82" start="start">mm</pageBreakToken>
, linear; pedicels 3-8 (-15) mm; outer sepals 9-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
5 mm, ovate, acute to shortly acuminate, densely hairy; corolla (1.3-)1.5-1.8 cm long, white, unlobed, midpetaline bands pubescent, terminating in a tooth; ovary glabrous. Capsule glabrous; seeds glabrous, nearly smooth but somewhat rugose on the angles. [
<bibRefCitation author="Verdcourt, B" editor="Hubbard, CE" journalOrPublisher="HMSO, London" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B373" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1963. Convolvulaceae. In: Hubbard, CE, Milne-Redhead, E, Eds., Flora of Tropical East Africa. HMSO, London: 1 - 161" title="Convolvulaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Tropical East Africa." year="1963">Verdcourt 1963</bibRefCitation>
: 42 (as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schulze-Menz" authorityYear="1939" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus zernyi" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zernyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus zernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Malawi (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Synge</emphasis>
WC 251, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Pawek</emphasis>
13111, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Richards</emphasis>
20646); Tanzania (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Lovett et al.</emphasis>
2089, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Mgaza</emphasis>
121). 1800-2100 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
We have widened the concept of this species from that of 
<bibRefCitation author="Verdcourt, B" editor="Hubbard, CE" journalOrPublisher="HMSO, London" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B373" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1963. Convolvulaceae. In: Hubbard, CE, Milne-Redhead, E, Eds., Flora of Tropical East Africa. HMSO, London: 1 - 161" title="Convolvulaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Tropical East Africa." year="1963">Verdcourt (1963)</bibRefCitation>
to include plants with a somewhat smaller corolla and calyx, including the type of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baker, Bull Misc. Inform. Kew 1894: 67. 1894. (Baker" authorityYear="1894" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus thomsonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thomsonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus thomsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is atypical in its relatively short calyx and corolla but is clearly an immature specimen of this taxon. This species appears to be frequent in the highlands of northern Malawi and southern Tanzania. It is very close to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sagittatus" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus sagittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in the larger sepals, 9-11 mm in length and the tomentose indumentum, which dries brown. The rather long, often arching peduncles are also very characteristic. An unusual feature is the occasional presence of paired peduncles. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger solitary flowers as well as the tomentose indumentum. It is also close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. H. Wright, Fl. Cap. (Harvey) 4 (2): 75. 1904. (Baker and Wright" authorityYear="1904" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus galpinii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="galpinii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus galpinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differing principally in the longer, gradually narrowed sepals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
As with many other African species, intermediates with other species are found. These have the same indumentum, relatively large corollas and sepals of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baker, Bull Misc. Inform. Kew 1894: 67. 1894. (Baker" authorityYear="1894" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus thomsonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thomsonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus thomsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but inflorescences of 2-3 flowers. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Phillips</emphasis>
2738 and 3920 from northern Malawi and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Richards</emphasis>
6071 from Zambia appear to be intermediate with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or possibly 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
